#Convert the catergorical features Day and Month to numerical values with the help of calendar library
# {jan, feb, mar,...., dec} -> {1,2,3,....,12}
# {mon, tue, wed,...., sun} -> {1,2,3,.....,7}
days = dict((day.lower(),index +1 ) for index, day in enumerate(calendar.day_abbr))
months = dict((month.lower(),index) for index, month in enumerate(calendar.month_abbr))

df['month'] = df.apply(lambda x: months[x['month']], axis=1)
df['day'] = df.apply(lambda x: days[x['day']], axis=1)

Impact of Correlation on the Feature Selection ¶

The Correlation matrix has immense impact on the feature selection. The features which has no influence on the target variable, should be removed from the final set of features. However, in this scenario, we have observed a lot of Outliers (specially in the target variable). We will first clean up those variables and re-do the correlation before finalizing the required features for our Model

Feature Selection Based on the Correlation Matrix¶

Clearly from the above, the following features have least influence on the target variable

*Day, ISI, RH*

Hence, these can be removed from our Feature Set. For the next steps, we will consider only the following variables as our features

X, Y, month, FFMC, DMC, DC, temp, wind, rain

To Note, a large negative correlation is just as useful as a large positive correlation. The only difference is that for a positive correlation, as the feature value increases, the target value will also increase. For a negative correlation, as the feature value decreases, the target value will increase.For feature reduction, select features with a correlation close to 0. This means that the feature does not have a useful relationship to the target, and will not help with any prediction.

To note, we do not see any set of features which are highly dependent on each other, i.e. none of the non-diagonal values in the above Correlation matrix is close to 1. Which means, the chosen feature set columns are "Not" dependent on each other and hence, there is no need to further reduce the feature set

Feature transformation¶

For the given dataset, we will be using Normalization technique to transform the features. Specifically, we will be using Min-Max Scaling

Justification: Normalization is beneficial when you want to scale the data to a specific range, often between 0 and 1. It preserves the original distribution and relative relationships between the values.

Use case: Normalization is frequently used in algorithms that require input features to be on the same scale, such as neural networks or support vector machines.

For our dataset, the features have multiple different scale (max vs min) and hence we have chosen the above mentioned procedure

4. Model Building and Performance Evaluation¶

Explicit Splitting of Data into Test and Train¶

There are multiple ways to split the data into testing and training set. First, we are going to try the naive method, which is a simple split of the dataset based on the percentage of the rows. We will first try a 80:20 split, which means, the model will train on 80% of the rows and then the model performance will be evaluated on the test data set which is the remaining portion (20%) of the dataset. We will also try 75:25 split and observe the result¶

K-Fold Cross Validation¶

With K-fold Cross-Validation the dataset is split into a K number of folds and is used to evaluate the model's ability when given new data. K refers to the number of groups the data sample is split into. For our Purpose, we will use a 10 fold cross validation.¶

In [ ]:
X = df_normal.iloc[:, 1:].values
y = df_normal.iloc[:,:1].values
scores=[] #to store r squared
rmse_list=[] #to store RMSE
cv = KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=42, shuffle=True)
for train_index, test_index in cv.split(X):
    X_train_k, X_test_k, y_train_k, y_test_k = X[train_index], X[test_index], y[train_index], y[test_index]
    lin_reg.fit(X_train_k, y_train_k)
    y_predict = lin_reg.predict(X_test_k)
    scores.append(lin_reg.score(X_test_k, y_test_k))
    rmse_fold = rmse(y_test_k, y_predict)
    rmse_list.append(rmse_fold)
print("R Squared Mean: ", np.mean(scores))
print("RMSE mean: ", np.mean(rmse_list))

R Squared Mean:  -0.03485724146592752
RMSE mean:  0.14424304837884178

Performance Evaluation Observation¶

Mean Absolute Error (MAE): The MAE value of 0.072 indicates that, on average, the model's predictions deviate by approximately 0.072 units from the actual values. Lower MAE values indicate better performance.¶

Mean Squared Error (MSE): The MSE value of 0.011 represents the average squared difference between the predicted and actual values. Smaller MSE values indicate better performance.¶

Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): The RMSE value of 0.10 is the square root of MSE and provides an estimate of the average prediction error. Lower RMSE values indicate better performance.¶

R-squared (R2) Score: The R2 score of -0.064 measures the proportion of variance in the target variable (area) that can be explained by the model. A negative R2 score suggests that the model performs worse than a horizontal line. Higher R2 scores (closer to 1) indicate better performance.¶

Based on the Above, we can conclude the model is fitting few points while some points are completely ignored. Linear Regression might not be a good candidate for this problem. This is most likely because of the low sample size and uneven distribution of variables. Also, we do not have much insight on the domain of this dataset so it is difficult to take decision on Truely impacting variables on the target set. Other regression models (Decision Tree Regression, Random-Forrest, SVM etc.) can be tried to see if this data fits well.¶
